---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="About">
  <div class="container prose about">
    <h1>About the QSC Atlas</h1>
    <p>
      The QSC Atlas shows, country by country, how governments are migrating to quantum-safe
      cryptography: which post-quantum standards dominate, which international standards processes
      a country takes part in, and where one exists, its migration timeline.
    </p>
    <p>
      It draws on institutional sources only: government bodies, national agencies, and standards
      organisations. Each country profile links to the primary documents it is built from, so you
      can read the source for yourself. The Atlas is rebuilt as new institutional documents appear,
      so it reflects the current public record rather than a one-off snapshot.
    </p>

    <h2 id="classification">How the Atlas classifies countries</h2>
    <p>
      Every country is described on two dimensions, because two different things are easy to
      confuse. An EU member coordinates through the European roadmap, yet the algorithms it
      deploys are the American NIST standards, because there is no European alternative. One label
      would drop half the truth, so the Atlas keeps both: the colour is the club, the badge is the
      technology.
    </p>

    <h3>Coordination posture (the map colour)</h3>
    <p>Which collective transition a country belongs to.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>NIST-led ecosystem</strong>: works to the standards and cadence set by the United States' NIST (FIPS 203, 204, 205). The largest group by far.</li>
      <li><strong>EU coordinated roadmap</strong>: follows the European Union's synchronised transition under the NIS Cooperation Group, with its 2026, 2030 and 2035 milestones. A coordination commitment, not a separate set of algorithms.</li>
      <li><strong>Sovereign bloc</strong>: builds and mandates its own national algorithms and runs its transition independently of NIST. This is where the global baseline actually fractures.</li>
      <li><strong>Engaged but unaligned</strong>: visibly working on the transition, but not yet committed to a bloc, a standard, or a timeline.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Standards role (the badge)</h3>
    <p>The country's relationship to the algorithms themselves.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Standard-setter</strong>: writes the standards others adopt. Today there is effectively one, the United States through NIST.</li>
      <li><strong>Standard-contextualiser</strong>: accepts the baseline but adds national requirements such as mandatory hybrid deployment, larger keys, or independent certification.</li>
      <li><strong>Standard-taker</strong>: adopts the baseline broadly as published, without a substantial national overlay.</li>
      <li><strong>Sovereign developer</strong>: designs and standardises its own post-quantum algorithms.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How to read the map</h3>
    <p>
      Colour shows coordination posture. The role badge on each profile shows the standards role,
      and the map can be recoloured by role. Confidence is shown alongside every classification and
      drives how strongly a country is coloured, so a low-confidence call looks tentative. Faint grey
      is no data, meaning no institutional source has been found yet, which is different from engaged
      but unaligned, an active but undecided country. Every profile links to the documents it is built
      from.
    </p>

    <h2 id="briefing">Request a briefing</h2>
    <p>
      The Atlas is maintained alongside a consulting practice on the quantum-safe transition. If you
      would like a briefing tailored to your organisation or sector, get in touch.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a class="briefing-link" href="mailto:hello@example.com?subject=QSC%20Atlas%20briefing">
        Request a briefing
      </a>
    </p>
    <p class="note">Replace the contact address above with your real one before launch.</p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .about h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
  }
  .about h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
  }
  .about h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
  }
  .about ul {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }
  .briefing-link {
    display: inline-block;
    border: 1px solid var(--ink);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);
    text-decoration: none;
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
  }
  .note {
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }
</style>
